column9: Description
column19: Material of playground floor (rubber, grass, dirt, sand, concrete, wood chip/mulch, asphalt)

column9: Located next to the Berkeley Rose Garden, Codornices Park is famous for the very tall cement slide. Make sure to sit on cardboard, normally found by the bottom, while riding down the slide. There are also two traditional wooden play structures.

Flickinger Park is a sport based park having 3 baseball diamonds and 2 basketball courts. The park contains plenty of parking and has two playgrounds. The picnic area overlooks the tot playground while the older kids playground is slightly further down.

Fairwood Park has an amazing BBQ area which would be great for large parties. It overlooks the big kids playground, which is sand base. It unfortunately doesn't overlook the tot playground which is sand and rubber based. There are a number of other picnic tables & BBQ pits throughout the park that, while smaller, have better vantages to the playground.

column3: Dorado Way and Alta Vista Dr

column9: Kennedy Park runs along the Napa River. The playground is by the second parking lot at the end of Streblow drive. The 350 acre park also offers five reservable picnic areas, stroller trails, softball, soccer, volleyball, boat launching, hiking, and the 18-hole Napa Golf Course.

Koret Children's Quarter in Golden Gate Park is one of the oldest, biggest, and best playgrounds in San Francisco - featuring a huge, gloriously terrifying slide down a hillside, an antique carousel, and an amazing climbing structure.

The main playground by Tassajara Rd and Central Pkwy has a water play area and two play structures for older and younger kids. There are two slides built into a rock climbing wall and a nice sized sand pit. The water play area is generally operational from the Memorial Day weekend through the Labor Day weekend. During the drought, check online for operating hours. There is a smaller playground past the soccar fields with a play structure, some climbing equipment and swings.
Cement slide!

Lake Merritt is an urban oasis, a treasure for the Oakland residents and visitors. Take a stroller hike around the lake, visit the dozen or so gardens, and bird watch along the shores. The playground is fairly ordinary, but has a great location by the lake. Children's Fairyland, a fabulous amusement park for kids under 8, is also located at Lake Merritt.

Coyote Point is a regional recreation area that provides a wide variety of opportunities: picnicking, swimming, windsurfing, bicycling, jogging, fishing, boating, and sailing.The highlights for kids are the Magic Mountain Playground and CuriOdyssey, a natural history musuem with a small zoo. Magic Mountain is separated into a two parts and has a castles and dragons theme. The 3 story high slide is sure to delight any child. Great place for hosting celebrations. Entrance is $5 per car.

Harbor View Park provides easy access to the Bay Trails. The park has 2 playground. The older kids playground is primarily for climbing. The younger kids play area has a dedicated sand pit. The park also has a baseball diamond, picnic tables & BBQ pits & dedicated parking.

column3: San Jose Ave & Sgt John V Young St
column9: This large park, home to the Balboa pool, includes a sand playground with climbing structures, four baseball fields, a soccer stadium, tennis courts, and a picnic area.
With a beautiful waterfront setting, Erckenbrack Park provides 3.4 acres of lawn area, sand beach, a children's playground, and restroom facilities.

This circular park is built on a hill and at the top is a spectacular view. Also at the top is a tennis and basketball court, and a flat ball field. On the side of the hill is a children's playground.

Located at the corner of Juniper and Sagewood streets, is a 5-acre neighborhood park with unique mounded turf areas. Amenities include picnic areas, play apparatus, restrooms, horseshoe pits and plenty of off-street parking.

Linda Vista Park is nestled in the Cupertino hills and is great for stroller trail walks. They also have 2 playgrounds. The first playground situated at the upper level of the parking lot is for older kids. The middle level contains older picnic tables & a large BBQ pit. The bottom level is the playground for tots. There is also a huge open grass area for kids to run around.

Montague Park is a huge park that has an attached school. There are a total of 5 play structures in this park. Two belong to the school, but are accessible outside school hours. 

On one side of the park there is a unique sand play structure near the restrooms. This play struture is semi enclosed and even contains tunnels for kids to use. Youg kids would surely love to utilze this unique and quite large sand pit play structure. There are a number of picnic tables and BBQs overlooking the play structure. 

At the center of the park, are the two play structures connected to the school. These are dedicated to older kids. 

At the far end of the park, there are two more play structures. One dedicated to older kids and one to younger kids.

Altamont Creek Park is a 6.9-acre neighborhood park attached to Altamont Creek Elementary School and is closed during school hours. The park offers two medium-sized soccer fields designed for kids 10 and under and accommodates two youth-sized baseball fields. It also offers tot lot equipment, barbecue pits, picnic tables and hiking and biking trails. Park users include Pony Baseball and Livermore Youth Soccer League.

Located on Nob Hill and surrounded by the Grace Cathedral, the Fairmont Hotel, and the Mark Hopkins Hotel, Huntington Park is a quiet place that features a playground for kids, plenty of benches to kick back on, and a nice area for your dogs. There are restrooms available, too.

Our favorite park in Los Gatos has a large playground area with a real, decommissioned USAF T-33 Jet. Your children will love the Carousel and Billy Jones Wildcat Railroad. Oak Meadow is also connected to Vasona Park, which has lots of reservable picnic areas. Parking lot is paid parking.

Osage Station Park is known for its beautiful, memorial rose garden and children's play area with train station.

This 35-acre park features four tennis courts, four baseball diamonds, several soccer fields, plus a path around the park. The tennis courts and sports fields can be rented. An additional parking lot is located near the tennis courts, off Orange Blossom Way. The twenty picnic tables and five barbecue pits are located near the children's play area and are available to rent.

The park is named after the ranch that grew Osage Oranges, and there are still three Osage Orange trees at the park.

column3: B St. & Martin Luther King Way

column9: Indian Springs Park has a small parking lot and 2 playgrounds. The playgrounds have a number of climbing structures. There is also an oval paved area in front of the playgrounds with a grassy center for kids to play.

Joe DiMaggio Playground features basketball courts where you can find pick-up games during the week, well-maintained tennis courts and a backboard for solo players to use. Baseball players can enjoy the two fields that are available! Finally, there is a Bocce Ball court if you know the rules of this strategic Italian game.

Locally known as "JK," Julius Kahn is adjacent to the Presidio, the nation's largest urban National Park. The playground is in excellent condition and provides kids and parents two structures to choose from--one designed for babies and toddlers, and another for school-aged kids. Both playgrounds are situated in a sand pit.

Lakewood Park is a large park with much to do. The tot playground is above sand and also has a small dedicated sand pit. The big kids playground has a spaceship theme and is located on rubber. 
The park also has a skate area, baseball diamond, tennis courts and basketball court. There is also a paved trail through the park to allow for bike riding.
Pleasanton’s largest developed park is Pleasanton Sports & Recreation Community Park approximately 103 acres in overall area.

Koret Children's Quarter in Golden Gate Park is one of the oldest, biggest, and best playgrounds in San Francisco - featuring a huge, gloriously terrifying slide down a hillside, an antique carousel, and an amazing climbing structure.
This recently opened park has everything, play structures for each age range, sand pit, water play, climbing structures, and picnic tables. Our only complaint is the limited shade available.

This park is great if you want to get some fresh air! Four blocks long, the numerous paths allow you to walk or run. There is plenty of open space to play with your child and lots of trees to provide shade on a hot day. Also, its a great place for a picnic! There is a small, fenced in playground for kids, designed by Miller Company Landscape Architects. It is in good condition with two tennis courts. There are picnic tables to sit at and restrooms available.

Come visit Howarth Park, the “jewel" of Santa Rosa. This 152-acre community park provides endless recreational opportunities with a beautiful lake for fishing & boating, a softball field, tennis courts, picnic areas, unique playground structures, miles of hiking and jogging trails, and an amusement area featuring a miniature train ride, carousel, animal farm & pony rides.

This park is great for picnics: company picnics, family reunions, and barbecues! Reservable Picnic Area with Barbecue, Softball/Sports Field, Sand Volleyball Court, Surfaced Basketball Court, Lighted Bocce Courts.

Location! This great park is right by Downtown Campbell and is a major access point to Los Gatos Creek Trail which connects Downtown San Jose to Lexington Reservoir in Los Gatos. The playground has a fun spinning wheel and a nice sand pit. There are a very small number of first-come, first-served picnic tables available in the park.

column3: W Santa Clara St & N Autumn St
column9: Guadalupe River Park is a three-mile ribbon of park land that runs along the banks of the Guadalupe River in the heart of downtown San Jose. The Rotary PlayGarden is located at Arena Green, the section of the park located between Santa Clara Street on the south, Julian Street on the north, and directly across Autumn Street from HP Pavilion. There are 2 brightly colored playgrounds for children both young and old, featuring swings, slides, a play fort and climbing structures.

This 4-acre neighborhood park, is located on Leonard Drive at Williams Street. The park provides neighborhood-oriented facilities, including picnic areas and tennis courts. The park is adjacent to the large open spaces of John Muir School. Amenities include 10 barbecue pits, night lighting, parking, 21 picnic tables, play areas and restrooms.
Located at 3750 Monterey Boulevard, this park offers both picnic and play areas. Green space and a baseball diamond are located on the adjacent school site.

Joinville Park is located next to Bayside Performing Arts Center. The park has a pool, 2 tennis courts, a baseball diamond and a big play structure. The play structure is interconnected for both the tots and big kids. The picnic tables that overlook the play area don't provide great supervision opportunities.

column2: Scotts Valley Tim Brauch Memorial Skate Park
column9: Tim Brrauch Memorial skate park shares it's grounds with Skypark. For older kids that want to skate, this is a great area. For younger kids, it's great that you have some playgrounds around the corner.

The highlight of Sharon park is the large pond where you are see fish, turtles and occasionally ducks and geese. There is a path around the pond where you can push a stroller or bike. One small play structure in fully fenced and shaded.

Located at the corner of 20th Street and Vermont in the Potrero Hill neighborhood, McKinley square features a playground with a large sand pit, and a large grassy open area for soccer, football, a game of catch, or to just let the dogs roam. There is a walking trail with benches.

Michelangelo is another nice addition to the Russian Hill area. It is extraordinarily maintained and locals consider it the jewel of the neighborhood. There is a half basketball court, a large tennis backboard to hit on, and a playground with sand area for children. There are benches and picnic tables where you can watch your kids and have lunch. The grass is really nice to sit/lay down on too!

Mission Playground, surrounded mostly by family housing, boasts nearly 100,000 sf of park space. Located off of 19th and Linda streets and bordering on Valencia Street in the Mission District, the park features a clubhouse, outdoor pool with lockers, playground, soccer field, tennis and basketball courts, and open lawn areas. Very little shade at this park.

Moscone Rec offers a plethora of activities for kids and adults. There are four baseball fields and four full tennis courts, two full basketball courts, and a remodeled playground.

Dogs are welcome too.

There are bathrooms at the rec center and this park also offers two putting greens.

Stafford Grove is the closest playground to Novato's downtown area. The park is equipped with a large playground and benches that are shaded by trees. Stafford Grove is a quaint neighborhood park, which offers a nice break for those shopping with children along Grant Avenue.

John Morgan Park, shares its field with Campbell Middle School. It contains two baseball diamonds and two playgrounds on opposite ends of the park. The first playground West Rincon Ave. is primarily dedicated to younger kids. The play area is sand based, with a complex climbing structure for older kids. There is also a water feature present here. The second playground, located Budd Ave. is primarily a big kids play area. The play area has a mulch base, and numerous slides and climbing walls. Both playgrounds have picnic tables, with BBQs, that overlook the play area. There are also bathroom close to each playground.
Turfed area for free play and a children's play area with swings, slide and climbing apparatus.

Located just behind the Bernal Heights Branch Library. A very welcoming playground, Bernal Heights is designed around a few trees that shelter small clusters of benches and picnic tables. The play equipment is in fairly good shape and quite inviting. There are restrooms located at the library itself.

Situated next to Mountain Lake where the southern edge of the Presidio meets the Richmond District, this park offers many different amenities. Children enjoy the sand-floor playground at the 12th Avenue entrance that feature slides, swings, and a multi-level play structure. There is a covered picnic/card playing pavilion opposite the 9th Avenue entrance. The great meadow is a favorite place to spend the afternoon for a picnic or to rent for children's birthday parties.

Sycamore Valley Park, located at Holbrook Drive and Camino Tassajara, has a children's play area with popular recreational fountain, a reflection pond with waterfall, and a jogging path that meanders through the park.
 
The picnic area adjacent to the baseball diamonds include eight picnic tables and barbecue pits. In addition, a new group picnic area has been added adjacent to the bocce ball courts that will accommodate up to 65 people.
Indoor swimming pool,

Thamien Park is a small neighborhood park which contains two play structures. One for older kids and one for younger kids. There are picnic tables overlooking the play structures. From the park you can access the Guadalupe River Trail.

Located next to Stern Grove, Parkside Square is a nice park to visit on a weekend afternoon. There are quite a few amenities that include a walking trail, brand new playground equipment and sand area for children, four tennis courts and a basketball court too; in addition, there is a baseball field, dogs are welcome, and there are clean bathrooms and water fountains available!

This recently-renovated mini park has great public art and murals on display! There is a children's playground with picnic tables and seating. The park provides two swings and a merry-go-round for children to enjoy. Also, kids can enjoy playing on the mosaic serpent, which shoots water from his tail! There are also many benches and picnic tables to rest, eat lunch, and watch your kids play.
This playground has a unique old west play structure dedicated to toddlers. They'll have a plast playing with the train and the old west buildings.

Portsmouth Square is a community treasure and meeting point. People come here to enjoy their free time and there is something to do for everyone. This is a good central place if you're going to spend time in Chinatown. If you have children, they will enjoy the playground. Checkers/Chess players come here too to enjoy the unique competitive vibe. There is Tai Chi practiced here; however, it is very early in the morning.

A beautiful wooded 4 acre park with a creek, this park is the perfect setting for your wedding, family picnic, or company party. This park offers barbecue and picnic facilities, a children's play area with water feature, two horseshoe pits, a sand volleyball court, restrooms & stage.

In the summer of 2007, the city renovated the lower playground giving kids and families a brand new, large and colorful place to play. There is also a baseball field, two tennis courts, and a basketball court; however, the real treat for the public is the recreation center that is extremely well maintained and has a variety of sports/activities to choose from!

There are plenty of picnic tables for lunch, in addition to the BBQ pits, and enough space for your pooch to run around.
Get some lunch from town and picnic in this nice park. New sponge surface is great.

Two small playgrounds at opposite ends of this park. The main attraction here is the aquatic park here which has an amazing shallow play area for kids including slides, climbing structures and water spray toys. There are two 30-foot giant pool slides as well.

Arguello Park is a sports park. There is a large baseball diamond and concession stand. There are a number of picnic tables & BBQ pits overlooking the baseball diamond, perfect for having a cookout while watching a game. The playground is located past the baseball diamond, is fully enclosed, situated on rubber & dedicated for younger kids.

Hester Park is located on Naglee Ave, just off Dana street. The playground is fully enclosed and contains two play structures; one for older kids and one for tots. There are park benches around the play areas to allow for supervision.

Richmond Playground includes two basketball courts, a tennis court, a large multipurpose court, and a climbing structure with sand pit for children.

There is a clubhouse with restrooms.

There is a rec center down the street at 251 18th Ave between California and Clement. During the summer there is a day camp for kids and during the fall/school year there are after school and tiny tots programs. Call for more information: (415) 666-7020.

Located in the Richmond District, Rochambeau Playground has a well-kept recreation area that offers two full basketball courts, a tennis court, four-square court, hopscotch blacktops, and a dual-level playground with great climbing structures and sand area. One playground is designed for younger tots and one for older children. There are restrooms at the recreation center and plenty of benches and picnic tables to rest at. The gate closes at 6:00 pm.

The playground at Moss Beach Park features a pirate boat, a miniature lighthouse, dolphin slides, swings and a tot area. Midcoast residents came together in 2004 and turned what had been a ramshackle collection of donated toys and play structures into a lovingly conceived and imaginative play area for kids of all ages. Consultation was provided by local play experts, i.e. the kids.
There are picnic tables, shade trees, expansive turfed playfields for soccer and casual play and a children's play area.

Laurie Meadow Park has a large grassy area, an oval walking trail, an enclosed dog park & 2 playgrounds. The playgrounds are older and a little dated. There are picnic tables surounding the play area and have BBQ pits. The park is connected to Casanova Park.
Polynesian themed Park has two separate enclosed playgrounds.

Crestview Park is set behind houses with a single entrace. The park has a large soccer field & a basketball court. The playground is partially enclosed with a big kids and little kids play area. The playground also has a dedicated sand pit & awnings to protect from the sun. There are picnic tables & BBQ pits overlooking the play area.

Rossi Playground has two baseball fields and a large grass area, three tennis courts, a full basketball court, an indoor pool, and a play area for children. There are two sections of the playground: one is for older kids and one is for younger tots.

Ortega park, has both a tots & big kids play area. The tot play area is enclosed and has a mulch base. There are also picnic tables within the enclosed play area, for you to supervise or simply have lunch. 
The big kids play area is also mulch base, and is located next to the the tot play area, which allows for easy supervision.
The park also has a dedicated climbing wall and a water feature. There is a huge picnic area with a BBQ pit, excellent for hosting a birthday party.

One of the best parks in the neighborhood with 4 separate playgrounds, stroller trail around the lake, boating in the summer and Aqua Adventure Water Park. One playground is right by the parking off Paseo Padre Parkway, there is a climbing net, big kid and toddler play structures. The largest playground is between Lake Elizabeth and Aqua Adventure. It has a fun forest theme. The third playground is a tot lot past the Boathouse in the direction of the Fremont Main Library. The last playground is the Always Dream Playground, an accessible playground great for younger tots and children with disabilities. It's on the other side of the park off Stevenson Boulevard by the soccar and softball fields.
Fremont Skate Park is located next to Fremont Central Park (Lake Elizabeth) playground.

St. Mary's Square is great place to visit if you're downtown. Any green space in this area is very valuable to the locals! This place is really gorgeous though. There are lots of trees and bushes, plenty of benches to relax on after a ton of walking, and a play structure if you have kids! There are restrooms available too.
Great neighborhood park with a climbing wall, sand pit, cement slide and play structure.

John Mise Park has an amazing soccer field with stadium lighting. The park also contains two basketball courts. 
The playground is dedicated towards older kids and there are picnic tables that overlook it. Bathroom are nearby as well.
This neighborhood park is almost 5 acres and is located at 1245 147th Avenue. A concrete volleyball court and tot lot are also available for use.

Memorial Park, in Cupertino, is located next to Quinlan Community Center. The park has a huge open grass area for kids to play as well as a baseball diamond. There are 2 picnic areas that overlook each of the two playgrounds. The playgrounds are good for all age groups.

Fremont Park has two play structures for both younger and older kids. The playground has an Atlantis type theme incorporating Pegasus statues and sunken dinosaur bones. The playground contains 6 slides, 2 of which are quite large and would be entertaining for big kids. The play structure is located on sand and there is also rubber to make it handicap accessible. There are swings for both tots and big kids. Surrounding the play structure are benches so you can supervise the kids. The park also has three picnic tables overlook the playground and one shared BBQs pit. Note the picnic tables are located on dirt, if you go after a morning shower the area is a little muddy. The park also contains a paved trail that is stroller friendly and can be used when learning to ride a bike.

There are two playgrounds – Redondo and Hardy – stand at the southern and northern ends. Hardy Playground, the larger of the two structures is designed primarily for children aged 5-12, although it does have a small tot lot and sandbox. It is tucked behind the redwood trees that line the south-east corner of the Hardy Park greenspace, at the intersection of Hudson and Claremont Streets. Redondo Playground is a tot lot designed for children 2-5 years old. It is located beneath the grove of redwoods at the intersection of Redondo Street and Clarke Street.

Frontierland Park is nestled up against the hills of Pacifica with lots of open space and picnic, BBQ, horseshoes and playground amenities. We have one large-group picnic area that can be reserved. Call 650-738-7381 for availability or to make a reservation. We also have several individual picnic tables which are first come, first serve. In the reservable large-group picnic area, we have 10 picnic tables, which seat about 6 to 8 people each. This area also has a counter prep area behind the 2 BBQ pits.

Parkside Aquatic Park, bordering the Marina Lagoon, has two playstructures on sand. Both play structures are for younger kids. There are picnic tables overlooking the play area with BBQ pits. You can also rent canoes & kayaks or unload your boat into the Lagoon.

Hawes Park is a sport field, with a baseball diamond. The park is connected to Hawes Elementary School. During off school hours, the school's playgrounds are accessible. The playground is dedicated for older kids. The playground itself is also enclosed and there are school picnic tables surounding the area.

Bol Park is a quiet neighborhood park. The play structures are good for all ages. Behind the park is a walking / biking trail that can be used. A unique feature of this park is that on Sunday's donkeys are brought to the park to interact with visitors.

Highlands Park is a sports based park, having 3 baseball diamonds, a soccer field & 5 tennis courts totalling 11.25 acres in size. The park has two parking lots and plenty of street parking. There are two playgrounds situated next to the restrooms for tots & big kids. The playground also has a sand pit.
The playground at Hillcrest Park is called Matteo's Dream. It is an all accessible playground where kids of all abilities can play together. There are lots of ramps, tunnels, and slides.

Lincoln Glen Park has two playground, one for older kids and one for tots. The entire park is enclosed, which is great for allowing the little ones to run around unsupervised. The tot playground is mulch and rubber based, while the older kids play structure is sand and rubber based. The park also has a water feature and picnic tables that overlook the play structures.

Holbrook Parlmer Park, is Atherton's only recreation site, and large at 22 acres. There is a large parking lot, lots of open grass area for kids to play, stroller trails and is dog friendly. 
There are two playgrounds within the park. The younger kids play structure is train themed, enclosed and has picnic tables inside.

Homeridge Park is a neighborhood park dedicated to older kids, aged 5-12. The wooden play structures are located on sand. The play area is partially enclosed, approximately 80% and is only open where the picnic tables and BBQs are located. This allows for easy supervision of the kids without worry. The park itself also has an open field area for kids to run and play. The park also contains a public restroom.
The playground features a baseball diamond, tennis and basketball courts, a sand playground, blacktop with four game squares, and a recreation center.

Jenny Strand Park is located at the end of a cul-du-sac and has a small parking lot. The park has a large grass areas and a small circular play area for kids. The play structure is partially fenced off, on the street side. The play structure is dedicated for younger kids age 0-5 with a wooden play structured residing  on sand. there are two swings, one for big kids and one for little kids. The park has individual bbq pits associate to each picnic table. While you have a clear view of the play structure it is too far away to leave young kids unsupervised.
Stern Grove is the host of the annual Stern Grove Festival. Every Sunday every summer, a music festival is held in the Stern Grove outdoor amphitheater.

Privately built by the South Beach Marina Association, South Beach Park is a lovely location on the waterfront for families and locals. There is a nice little playground for tiny tots with a small sand area and climbing structure appropriate for their ages.

There is also lots of grass for kids to run around in.

There are benches here to sit down and relax, and this spot is a nice walk to AT&T Park or the Ferry Building.

column3: Voss Ave and S Foothill Blvd
column9: Monta Vista Parks has 2 playgrounds, 2 baseball diamonds, 2 tennis courts & the Monta Vista Recreation Center within the park grounds. The playgrounds are on Woodridge Ct. There are two picnic tables that are situated between the playgrounds. Next to the playgrounds is a grassy area for kids to run and play.

This park is in the heart of the SOMA neighborhood. It has a small playground with recent improvements. It also has a sand pit and some unique climbing structures. There are plenty of paths and picnic tables to enjoy and appreciate your surroundings. This park is well-kept and has a ton of beautiful trees and bushes that surround the park.

Dogs are welcome too! There is plenty of space for your pup to run around and play fetch!

After a nice afternoon at South Park, head over to one of the cafes or restaurants around the perimeter!

South Sunset Playground has been recently renovated. It sports a brand new artificial turf field designed to hold two baseball diamonds and three U-10 soccer fields. There are two basketball courts, a tennis court, and a multi-use court. The playground has very bright colors. There is a clubhouse and restrooms available.
Modern and new play structure sets this park apart. There is a seesaw, spinning seat, rolling slide and lots of ramps.

Located on the beautiful San Francisco Bay, Baylands Park provides over seventy acres of developed parkland offering active recreation, pathways and picnic areas for families and large groups. Baylands Park has a Naturalist theme which is enhanced by the many acres of native grasses, open meadows and wonderful vistas. An additional 105 acres of seasonal wetlands is protected as a Wetlands Preserve providing habitat for plants and wildlife. Baylands Park is a successful joint venture between Santa Clara County which owns the property and the City of Sunnyvale which manages and maintains the Park.

The Discovery Play Area will catch your child's imagination. This creative playground is wheelchair-accessible. Play features include climbing structures, see-saw snake, spring toys, sand terraces and talk tubes. Young explorers can find fossil imprints in the archeological dig and follow dinosaur tracks.  Three smaller play areas feature swings, a climbing net and a play town.

column3: Wunderlich Drive and Castle Glen Avenue

column9: Ponderosa Park shares its space with Ponderosa Elementary School. The park itself has two soccer fields, a baseball diamond, basketball court, two tennis courts & two play structures in a western motif. The play area has has swings for both younger and older kids. The restroom, lated next to the play area, includes change tables. There are small picnic tables surounding the play area, and a larger reservable picnic area with BBQ pit closer to the parking lot.

Larry J. Marsalli Park's playground is located at the back of the park behind the parking lot and baseball diamond. The playground is dedicated for older kids and has a baseball theme to it. The play structure resides on sand and mulch. The playground also has tot swings, and possibly the more adventurous 2-5 yr olds could also play here. There are two sets of picnic tables that overlook the playground. Each set contains two picnic tables and 1 BBQs pit.the park also contains public restrooms.  The playground is partially fenced in, completely from the street with the opening only to the Parking lot, so kids can safely run free. One downside of this park is that it's located btw two major streets so it gets a little loud, but is completely safe due to the park being primarily fenced in.

Raynor Park is primarily a sport field, having 2 baseball diamonds. The park also has 2 play structures. The younger kids play structure is fully enclosed, has an awning and is located next to the restrooms. The older kids play area, has a dinosaur motif, a dedicated sand pit, is partially enclosed and also has an awning.

Laureola Park is a nice neighborhood park. The parking lot is located on Old County Rd behind Heating Supply Co. The park has a large baseball field, a grassy area for kids & a fully enclosed tot & big kids playground. There are picnic tables & BBQ pits overlooking the play areas. The playground theme has a forest / tree fort theme. There are also picnic tables within the play area.

The older kids playground at Krusi is very extensive with lots of bridges, slides and climbing structures. There is a separate fenced tot lot. Two picnic area can be rented, other areas are first-come, first serve. Also at Krusi are baseball/softball fields, tennis courts, and shuffleboard.

Maywood Park is a large park that shares the grounds with an elementary school. In one corner there is a play structure dedicated for kids 2-5 and 5-12. They playground also contains a riding horse for tots as well as tot swings. The play area is located on sand and has some rubber for handicap accessibility. There are picnic tables that overlook the play structure and you can supervise the kids from here.

The school itself has two play structures that can be used off school hours. These structures are dedicated for kids age 5-12 with an occasional slide that younger kids could use.

The park also has public restrooms but they are further away from the play structures, a short walk away. The park has paved trails throughout which can be used for biking or stroller walks. Throughout the park, there a numerous picnic tables with personal bow pits.

A hidden oasis by Foothill Exp, you walk through the parking lot, turn right down the pathway to find the playground, picnic area and large lawn. Two separate play structures for older and younger kids await you.

Sommerset Park is a small park located at the end Stokes Ave., which is also the only entrace to the park. The park has one play structure and even though it claims to be for younger kids, I believe older kids will enjoy it too. The park has an oval for taking a brisk walk, a basketball hoop & a grassy area for kids to run and play.

Monta Loma Park shares its space with Monta Loma Elementary School. The park itself has a play structure dedicated for younger kids. It has a sand pit and has picnic benches nearby. Transitioning over to the school, you have two playgrounds. One dedicated to big kids, and one for younger kids. The younger kids play area is enclosed. The park itself also has a large grass area for kids to run and play or partake in a game of soccer or baseball.

This playground has a play structure with a sand pit. There is also a softball field, tennis court, and basketball court. A nice area to take dogs for walks; however, it is not an official "off-leash" area. In addition, there is a clubhouse and rest rooms on site.

Nealon Park is just off of Middle Ave. The park has it's own dedicated parking and the playground is fully enclosed. There are two play structures, one for older kids and one for younger. There is also a dedicated sand pit with an awning. There are numerous park benches and also picnic tables within the playground enclosure.
The park also has a baseball diamond and 5 tennis courts. It's also a short walk from Safeway and Peet's Coffee.

Access is via Newhall Parkway south of Clayton Road or from Turtle Creek Road. Galindo Creek meanders through the park. Approximately 30 acres of park is improved with ponds along the creek, a play structure, picnic areas, bocce courts, and turfed athletic fields. There is one reservable group picnic area in a secluded creekside setting with large oak trees.

Sunnyside Playground was renovated in 2007 and now offers kids and families a much-improved park and recreation center. There is a colorful play structure, a large sand area with fountain, and a fun merry go-round. There is also a tennis and basketball court, a large grass area for playing catch or frisbee, and dogs are welcome too! There are plenty of picnic tables and restrooms available on-site!

Located off Monarch Bay Drive near Fairway Drive, this 30-acre regional park that borders the beautiful San Leandro Shoreline. Amenities include picnic areas with barbecue grills, play apparatus, three newly renovated large group picnic areas, a large grassy area and a mile-long par course.

This small, one-acre park is located on Breed Avenue at Sunnyside Drive. The park has two backstops for playing baseball or softball, a barbecue pit and a picnic table. There is a fenced tot lot, which is shared by Washington School for use during recess and physical education classes.

Palm Park is a small enighborhood park, the play structures are good for kids of all ages. Surounding the park there are a number of picnic tables, which is great for supervision. There is only one picnic table that has its own BBQ, which is also shaded by the trees.

This playground can be difficult to find but is worth the effort. It's tucked behind the parking lot of Harvest Middle School. This fully enclosed playground has lots of pretend and physical play opportunities. There are animal statues, wooden cars, play houses, a castle themed play structure and a climbing wall.

column3: St Anthondy Dr. & St Phillip Ct.

column9:
River Glen Park has 2 baseball diamonds, 2 basketball courts, 2 tennis courts and 2 playgrounds. The tot playground is enclosed and has a mulch base and a separate sand pit area. The older kids playground has a number of slides, including two fully enclosed slides. 
The restrooms are located close to the play structures which is great. We believe that picnic area #2 is a great place to reserve for special events.

Seven Seas playground, as the park name suggests, is a water themed playground. The play area is build around a pirate ship theme, with a rubber base. The play area is good for all ages, has a sand pint, is enclosed and has some covering overhead to protect from the sun.
The park also has it's own water feature. There are a number of picnic tables with dedicated BBQs. The parking lot is small, but there is plenty of street parking.

Red Morton Community Park is almost 32 acres of fun for kids. The park has 5 baseball diamonds, 2 soccer fields, 4 tennis courts, a skate park and playgrounds. 
The two playground are located on opposite sides of the park. The first playground, dedicated to older kids is located near the tennis courts near McKinley & Roosevelt. The playground has a unique rock climbing wall and an awning to keep kids cool. There are also picnic tables around the play area. The other playground, is dedicated to younger kids. There are picnic tables with BBQ pits overlooking the younger kids playground. 
There is a large reservable picnic area with an awning near one of the baseball diamonds.

Rex Manor Tot Park is primarily focused for tots. The playground has 3 slides; 2 are for tots and one is for bigger kids. The play area is sand based, but doesn't contain a dedicated sand pit. There is one picnic table that overlooks the play area.

Peers park has a huge grass area. Primarily used for soccess games. The park also contains a restrooms with change tables. 
There are two playground: for older and younger kids and one picnic table situated between them. The older kids playground has a unique rock climbing feature as well as numerous slides. Behind the tennis courts, more picnic tables can be found, if you're having a party for a larger group.

column3: Cres Village Cir & River Oaks Pkwy
column9:
River Oaks Park has a new playground for tots and big kids. There are numerous picnic tables that overlook the play area and one BBQ pit. The restrooms are located near the playground. Even though there is no parking, street parking is readily available. 
The park also has a large grass area, stroller trails, 2 tennis courts and a 1/2 basketball court.
Entertain your kids with a train, merry-go-round and Triple Pines Ranch Animal Farm. Ofcourse there is playground too.
Nice sized playground with lots of options. The park has lots of picnic tables. a nice path for biking or stroller hike, and a skate park.

Originally dedicated in 1938, this is one of the City's oldest parks. It is located at the intersection of Bancroft and Callan avenues, across from Bancroft Middle School. San Leandro Creek runs along the north side of the park. The park features extensive sitting areas and picnic facilities and two separate play areas. There are five barbecue pits, 10 picnic tables and restroom facilities.
Three Oaks Park is a nice neighborhood park, which contains two playgrounds. There are two picnic tables situated between the playgrounds and a grass field to run around in.

Stevenson Park shares its grounds with two elementary schools: Theuerkauf Elementary School & Stevenson Elementary School. Thus, during non school hours, there are plenty of playgrounds to choose from. The tot playground, part of the school, is enclused. It has a tree fort theme and has a covered sand pit.There are three more playgrounds adjecent to the field, each having multiple slides and climbing walls. Two of the playgrounds have rubber bases and one is mulch.

column3: Fox Ave. & N San Pedro St.
column9: Ryland Park is a primarily enclosed park and shares its space with Rotary Ryland Pool. The playground is train themed. The park has two play structures for older kids and one for younger kids, which is enclosed and has a sandpit. There are picnic tables and BBQ grills overlooking the play structures.

Stulsaft Park is an enclosed is a fully enclosed park which has two levels. The top level is dedicated to younger kids, and has a water play feature, playground and sand pit. There are also covered picnic tables so you can watch over the kids. The second level, accessed through stairs or 3 slides, is dedicated to older kids, and also has covered picnic tables.

Ryder Park is located just off Bay Trail and Seal Point Park trail. The playground is deidicated for younger kids and has an interesting climbing structure in the center of the playground. There are 2 large picnic sections with BBQ pits that overlook the playground. The restrooms are located next to the playground for easy access.
There is a grassy area with large trees, colorful flowers, picnic tables, benches and a small children's play area.

Three separate play structures, water play and a climbing structure offer a lot of variety. There is also a skate park, soccar field and rollar hockey rink. Unfortunately the park is next a water treatment plant and it can get smelly in some parts of the park.

This park has just been renovated and completed in June 2008. Upper Noe offers the neighborhood a brand new playground with a sand pit, an indoor gym, a baseball diamond and multipurpose field, basketball and tennis courts, and a recreation center with restrooms.

A hilltop park with views of the City (including the famous "Postcard Row"), Alamo Square features many things to do. There is a full tennis court, plenty of walking trails and benches, flower beds, and a dual-level kids' lot that had six swings, three slides and a pair of climbing structures. The upper level is for older kids (age 5-12), while the lower level is for the younger ones (age 2-5). Wheelchair access is available at the gate leading into the upper level.

War Memorial Playground is a unique playground. It's an ant themed playground. The park is enclosed expect for the entrance. WMP is a small playground. They have a slide for the young kids, a challenging climbing structure for the older kids and a sand pit for tots. The picnic table is located in the center of the park to overlook the entire playground. There is a hill that separates the playground from the grass area where kids can run around. The park contains a parking lot and the public restrooms are right next to the playground.

Victoria Manalo Draves Park, a two acre park in SOMA, opened in October, 2006. It is located on Folsom Street between 6th and 7th streets. The park features a ball field, basketball court, bathrooms, a childrens' play area featuring a teepee-style jungle gym and a slide, a community garden, a landscaped area, picnic area, and play field.

Whisman Park shares its grounds with Whisman Park. The playground is dedicated towards big kids. There are a number of picnic tables & BBQ pits surounding the playground, which are reservabe. There is a concrete trail through the park for bike riding and a grassy area for kids to play.

Selma Plinder Park shares its grounds with Olinder Elementary School, which provides for more playground access. The park itself has one playground dedicated to older kids. The school has an additional 2 playgrounds that are accessable. One is for tots and the other is a climbing structure for older kids. There is a reservable picnic area that overlooks the park's playground. 
This park has an extensive set of walking trails that are paved.

Walter Haas Park and Playground was renovated in 2005 and became a spectacular neighborhood park that people of all ages may enjoy. This park has a little something for everyone: a basketball court, large grass area, dog park, and a two tier playground: one for toddlers and one for older children.
This downtown park is a great escape from the fast-paced atmosphere of the city. It has beautiful landscaping and a children's playground at the end of the park. There are restrooms available too.
This park has ball fields, jogging path, picnic and barbecue facilities (including one reservable group site), a popular children's play area and large expanse of green for free play.

column3: Robert Davey Jr Dr & Aughinbaugh Way

column9: Located next to Shorebird Nature Center and Adventure Playground, Shorebird park has a nice play area featuring disabled-accessible playground equipment for both tot and school-age children, including swings, and climbing structures.

Really interesting tot focused playground where there lots of "left over" toys for childs to play with including ride on cars, push wagons and play kitchens more. There is also a regular play structure with slides, ramps and climbers.
Barn themed playground with an awesome water play feature. There is a net and wall climber and a separated fenced area for toddlers.

Rengstorff park is one of the largest parks in Mountain View, and as such has playgrounds to boot. There are a total of 5 play areas at the park, not including the pool. The play structures are primarily on rubber and sand, and have climbing walls, slides and swings. Towards the back of the park, away from Rengstorff & Crisanto is an enclosed playground, which is part of Learning Links Preschool. This enclosed play area included music instruments and a play structure. 
Rengstorff park has three major parking lots. One on Rengstorff Street, the other two on Crisanto Ave. The park has a large picnic and BBQ area between the two parking lots on Crisanto Ave.
A picturesque downtown neighborhood park with a playground, picnic tables, basketball court, and lawn area.

Baldwin Park has a basketball court, softball field, bocce courts, Baldwin Dog Park and a children's play area. There is reservable group picnic or barbecue area on a raised platform overlook, and several individual picnic tables with barbecues scattered throughout the park.

Concord Community Park is home to an Olympic size swimming pool, with diving facilities and a wading pool. There are two large playgrounds and two reservable group picnic/barbecue areas and many individual picnic tables with barbecues scattered throughout the park.
Rolling turf and a paved path around the lake, which is home to many species of waterfowl and several turtles. There are two children's play areas.

Central Park is located east of the Recreation Center, this 13-acre park is considered Millbrae’s top recreational area. Residents and visitors enjoy using this park for family outings, birthdays, weekend BBQ’s, play, and relaxing. During the summer months Millbrae hosts Concerts in the Park and other various activities bringing numerous people to this beautiful area. You will rarely see this park empty.

Sunnybrae Park is an enclosed neighborhood park dedicated for younger kids. There are three play areas and a sand pit for kids to use. There are 7 picnic tables overlooking the area to help with supervision.

Ted Fairfield is located next to Green elementary school. There are three play structures, all are fairly small and more suitable for preschoolers than older kids. There is a volleyball court, basketball court and baseball field as well. Limited shade available.

Belgatos Park is located off of Blossom Hill Road at the end of Belgatos Road. Limited on site parking is available.
 
Natural woodlands and wildlife abound in this beautiful 17 acre park. The park offers a variety of experiences for hikers, bicyclists, and equestrians on the 2 miles of trails. These trails connect to the Santa Rosa Open Space and the Heintz Open Space. Within the park is a playground, restroom, picnic tables, and lawn areas.

Beresford Park shares its grounds with Beresford Recreation Center. The park has 4 tennis courts, 4 bocce ball courts, 2 baseball diamonds, a skate park and 3 palygrounds. The tot playground is fully enclosed while the older kids playground has picnic tables to allow for easy supervision. There is an open field area for kids to run and play and surounding the big kids playground is a baved trail for riding your bike.

Tucked into a residential, downtown neighborhood, this small park represents Lafayette’s first neighborhood park. It’s a popular spot for picnic lunches and draws families with young children due to its whimsical Pirate Ship that captures the imaginations of young children with a top deck, steering wheel, climbing ropes and port holes. The play equipment area has a low perimeter fence that keeps the children safely enclosed. In the back, beneath a shade structure, is a children’s picnic table and side serving table that can accommodate small parties. There are no restroom facilities and use of the facilities is on a first-come, first-served basis.

The 68-acre site of Lafayette Community Park contains a diverse array of topography, wildlife and recreation opportunities. The south-end has two sports fields that are used for baseball in the Spring and soccer in the Fall. There is a group picnic area that can be reserved and several single picnic tables. A Tot Playground with an adjoining lawn is near the picnic area and fields. A footbridge leads people from the parking lot, located at 480 Saint Mary’s Road, to the fields, picnic area and public restrooms.
This park offers barbecue pits, picnic tables, rentable equestrian facilities, hiking/biking/horseback riding trails, restrooms, horseshoe pits and a rentable dog area.

column3: Carson Pass Way & Fallen Leaf Dr

column9: Mission Dolores Park is one of the most popular parks in San Francisco with a local Mission District feeling. The playground has great climbing structures and sand area. Lots of grassy area for picnics. Best during the week as it can be overcrowded with picnickers on the weekends.
A quiet neighborhood park with a playground, basketball court, picnic tables and large lawn areas.
Two lighted tennis courts, picnic areas, playground area, two ballfields, restrooms, bicycle/jogging paths,1-mile exercise course and a 2-mile pathway leading up to Hidden Lakes Park.
Neighborhood picnic area, playground area, multi-use field, bike racks and lighted pathways. All picnic areas are on a first come first serve basis. Click above for a map to this park.
Adjacent to John Muir School, playground and multi-use field.

Four ballfield complex with concessions and restroom, soccer field, picnic areas, playground areas, horse- shoe pits and bocce ball courts, restroom, the Marina and fishing pier. Twelve- hundred seat amphitheater and skateboard park. Contact Recreation Services to reserve a picnic area (925)372-3510.

Pleasant Hill Road East and Church Street. Ballfield, basketball court, three lighted tennis courts, playground area, picnic areas and restrooms. Contact Recreation Services at (925) 372-3510 to reserve a picnic area.
West end of Buckley Street. Swimming and diving complex, picnic areas, horseshoe pits, lighted softball field, restroom, playground area and gazebo.

column3: South Ashton, south of Millbrae Ave
column9: Rotary Park, situated on South Ashton just south of Millbrae Avenue is the perfect spot for children ages 2 to 5. Rotary Park offers smaller sized play equipment, a shaded picnic area, and a small grassy area. There is also a path for those who are looking to take a nice stroll or jog.

A destination playground. In addition to several play structure, they have a suspension bridge, slide made up of rollers, wavey slide, climbing wall, mini tunnel, mini maze train and more. Closed on non-holiday Tuesdays, September to May.

Blossom Hill Park is located between Shannon Road and Blossom Hill Road east of Blossom Hill School.
 
A fully developed neighborhood park with six lighted tennis courts, a baseball field, playground area and picnic tables, B-B-Q pits, restroom facilities and large lawn areas.

Boothbay Park offers 11.2 acres of playground area, a sand volleyball pit, lawn area, a basketball court, four tennis courts, a tiny tot play area, barbecue pits, a small amphitheater seating area, and restroom facilities.

The large covered picnic pavilion area is ideal for family or company picnics and accommodates up to 100 people. Interested? Call (650)286-3380 to check availability.
Big kids will enjoy the rocket themed play structure and climbing wall. There is a smaller play structure for toddlers and a water play area.

The Community Park is located next to the Orinda Community Center at 28 Orinda Way. The Park includes a large open grass area, two playground areas (one featuring a water play area), picnic and barbecue areas along with three tennis courts with lights. The gazebo, meadow, and tennis courts are available for reservation. The picnic area adjacent to the large tot lot is available on a first-come, first-serve basis.
Have audio but needed images
Beautiful local park with an excellent playground, paved trails for bike riding or a stroller walk. Lots of mature trees and a creek runs through the park.

This 6.3 acre neighborhood park includes a picnic and barbeque area, surfaced court and children's play area. Visit this hidden gem! Great play structure, large grassy open area, and lots of shade trees. Rentals on weekends only; 30 person maximum capacity. Alcohol and Big Jumps are not permitted at this park.

Softball diamond, 3 reservable Picnic Areas, 2 open Picnic Areas, Basketball Court, 2 Children's Playgrounds and Community Gardens.

Only open Monday - Friday 9am - 5pm.
This park has a small sand pit and no play structures. There are several trails adjacent to the creek there is good for bike riding or stroller hikes.

The McKinley Playground is a colorful custom designed playground, which is based on East Sacramento’s 125 year old past. It includes an “Alhambra Theater” entry archway, river boat, street trolley, the “Tower” bridge, large tree house, rubber surfacing with animal graphics, large climbing wall and boulders and concrete turtle. The playground also features a custom seat wall and sand area with a tile mural installed by local Sacramento artists.

The theme of the playground is "the solar system". There are three seperate play areas for infants under the age of 2, a tot lot for pre-school age children, and an adventure play area for school age children. Unique play features include a merry-go-around, swings, spring riders, group rocking units, self propelled spin play units, independent climbing structures and play units with sound features.

Originally a part of the Dibble Hospital Facilities and purchased in 1948, Burgess Park is one of the first city-owned recreation areas in Menlo Park. Located adjacent to the Civic Center complex, the park provides diverse facilities easily accessible to all Menlo Park residents.

With 166.5 developed acres this regional park includes many amenities, including the Sacramento Zoo, Fairytale Town, Funderland, Picnic Areas for small events and large events, Wading Pool, Basketball Court, 6 Softball Field, Soccer Fields, Adventure Play Area, Lakes, Amphitheater, Rock Garden, Jogging Path, Village Green, Golf Course, Off-street Parking, Restrooms.

column3: Murphy Rd and Poppy Glen Rd

column9: Millennium Playground was built by 1,500 volunteers in May 2000 during a one week period. The playground was designed by the children of San Anselmo and incorporates San Anselmo themes, such as a train depot, seminary tower and Town Hall tower.

West Sunset Playground has a large soccer field, three baseball diamonds, two tennis courts, a full basketball court, three small basketball courts, a running track, a playground for kids, and a small recreation center.

This multi-level park built into the side of a hill contains two sand play areas, three game and sports areas, and a big community recreation center and indoor gym. The Rec center runs an after school program that helps kids with homework and offers snacks and activities.

1 Basketball Court, Clubhouse/Activity Room, Kitchen, 2 Playgrounds, 4 Ping Pong Tables, Restrooms, 1 Tennis Court, 1 Volleyball Court.

Despite its small size, Woh Hei Yuen provides a variety of activities, attracting everyone from the elderly to small children. Views to and from the park's adjacent streets are kept open, while park structures and planting help to define sub areas and create a sense of depth. The principal landscape area has many features encouraging exploration, including a pavilion; wood bridge over a dry creek, stone walls, and granite boulders carved into human faces and oversized fruits. Concrete and special paving link the park's main activities, as well as providing spaces for uses such as tai chi and ball play.

Burton Park is one of the most popular parks in San Carlos. There are two play structures, one for tots and one for big kids. The big kids play structure has an awning to keep them cool during hot days. There is also a sand pit nearby. The tots play area, is located near the restrooms, and is completely enclosed. All the playgrounds have a rubber surface.

column3: Townsend Park Cir at Gordy Dr
column9: Townsend Park is located next to the San Jose Municipal Golf Course. The playground has 2 playgrounds; one for tots and one for big kids. Surounding the play area, there is a pergola for covered supervision.

Seminary Oaks Park is a small neighborhood enclosed park. The playground is good for all ages. A cool feature of the play structure is three slides connected into one, so kids can race each other down. The park also has benches surounding the play structures to allow for supervision.

Located at the corner of Park Street and San Leandro Boulevard, provides open green space and recreational facilities for the neighborhoods surrounding it. There are two barbecue pits, four picnic tables, a baseball field, a basketball court, a play area and restrooms.

An important neighborhood park located on Wicks Boulevard at Elvina Drive. Over the years, four regulation ball fields have been developed here for organized baseball league play. There are also four barbecue pits, six picnic tables, a half court basketball court, restrooms and a concession booth.

Located at the intersection of Davis Street and Orchard Avenue, is the City's oldest park. Renovated in 1992, this community park has several unique features, including a lighted regulation softball field, a skateboard park, and a historical railway society building. In addition, the picnic areas, playground, and green space provide for neighborhood recreation needs. There are six barbecue pits, six picnic tables, a tot lot and restrooms.

Located on Bancroft Avenue at 145th Avenue. The park includes a variety of facilities not found in many other San Leandro parks, including bocce and horseshoe courts. There are also four barbecue pits, six picnic tables, a tiny tot area and restrooms.
Two large play structures are located in this quiet neighborhood park. Next to the playground are four tennis courts and green open space.

Warden Park is a small park that provides recreation amenities for nearby residents. It is located at the corner of Warden Avenue and Tudor Road. There are two barbecue pits, two picnic tables, a basketball court and a tot lot.

This 15-acre neighborhood park is located at 14900 Zelma, near Manor Boulevard. Its amenities include a new aquatic center with a variety of water features and a community room, tennis courts, barbecue pits, basketball courts, playground apparatuses, two softball areas and an open grassy field.

West Hillsdale Park is hidden from the street and only accessible through one of the six walking entrances. The park has a large grassy area, a basketball court, an oval walking trail & a small playground for all age groups.
Great park with four play structures offering something for all age groups. In the center of the play structures is a water play area.
Has a baseball and soccar fields. Large diamond shaped climbing structure and a small toddler play structure.
One of the best parks in San Ramon. This 16 acre park has 2 playgrounds, BMX Track, bocce courts and a baseball field.
Located in a quiet residential neighborhood, Picadilly Square Park has a prehistoric theme. There is a dinosaur fossil in the sandpit and themed play structured. General lack of shade in this park.

One of the best playground, and a must visit. There is a multi level wooden castle play structure, with picnic tables all around it to watch your kids from and a smaller version for toddlers. There are also sea creature statutes for kids to climb on and a turtle pond.
At Chase Palm Park there is a Shipwreck themed playground with a boat and sea creatures, an carousel, and a pond full of turtles.

Fairway Glen Park's playground is dedicated for older kids. There are a number of slides and climbing walls. There is also a large field for kids to run and play as well as picnic tables overlooking the playground. Levi's stadium can be seen from the park.

column3: Canyon Del Rey Blvd. & Hilby Ave.

column9: Dan Foley is one of our principal parks in the GVRD system. It features a community center, fishing lake (state fishing laws enforced- see California Dept. of Fish and Game), natural grass baseball field (with lights), playground, and synthetic lighted soccer/ softball field.
Colorful local park with three play structures, for toddlers, preschoolers and older children, respectively. All are located together which is great for families with kids of different ages.

A very special park that has everything you can think of - swimming pool, tennis courts, rose garden, picnic areas, community center, equestrian center, skate park, off-leash dog park, bike paths, sand volleyball court, fishing pond, nature pond, six athletic fields, and connection to the Iron Horse Trail! Ofcourse there is an amazing all accessible playground as well.

Children's play areas, connection to walking trails, open turf area, picnic areas, swimming (May-September), tennis. Larkey Park is also home to the Lindsay Wildlife Museum and the Walnut Creek Model Railroad Society.

column3: Rossmoor Pwy and Tice Valley Blvd

column9: This is a very small park, near downtown Mountain View. This park is completely fenced in, has two small play structure for toddlers and a few picnic tables overlooking the play area.
Great neighborhood park, with lots of unique climbing structures.

Magic Bridge Playground is located within Meadow Park. It's enclosed and built primarily of rubber. The playground has an amphitheatre for story time. The park contains a number of sensory activities, a water feature, enclosed swings and climbing structures. There are also picnic tables within the playground. 

Just outside Magic Bridge Playground there are a number of play structures, picnic tables and BBQ pits that can be utilized after playtime is complete.

Casanova Park, connects to Meadow Park and is good for stroller walks. The playground itself is fully enclosed with a dinosaur theme. There is a bathroom nearby and a picnic area overlooking the playground.
Arcturus Park offers 3/4 acre of playground area, small lawn area, and a tiny tot play area.

This beautiful 5.8 acre park offers a chance for a moonlight (or midday, for that matter!) stroll along the Lagoon with a view of downtown Foster City as a backdrop. Catamaran Park offers a large turf area, beach area, picnic area, basketball court, play apparatus, two lighted tennis courts, sand volleyball pit, and restroom facilities.
Edgewater Park is 9.5 acres with large lawn areas, lighted softball diamond, basketball courts, playgroundarea, and tennis courts.
Farragut Park offers a large lawn area, picnic tables, benches, small sand box, play apparatus, and restroom facilities.

Gull Park offers a sand beach and two playground areas, as well as swings, slides, a large lawn area, and restroom facilities. The picnic tables at Gull Park are reservable for groups of up to 50 people. Call for more details.
Neighborhood park with a small play structure and set of swings. There is a basketball court, and a gazebo suitable for a small picnic.

In a waterfront setting, Marlin Park's offer a sand beach, playground area and large lawn area. One large play structure with both small and large slides. The picnic tables at Marlin Park are reservable for groups of up to 50 people. Call for details.
Tucked into the southern-most point of Foster City, Port Royal Park offers 4 acres of soccer fields, restrooms, play apparatus, and walkways for a lovely afternoon stroll.

Play Ball!! Sea Cloud Park has been called the "sporting gem" of the Peninsula. It is the home of the Foster City Little League and offers more than 23 acres of baseball diamonds, soccer fields, lawn area, play apparatus, snack shack, batting cages, and restrooms.
Shad Park provides 2.1 acres of lawn area, playgrounds, basketball court, and a multi-purpose court.

Brooktree Park shares its grounds with Brooktree Elementary School. The park has an enclosed playground good for tots with picnic tables and BBQ pits overlooking the area. The school has 2 playgrounds; one is primarily a climbing playground the other contains a couple of slides.
With 2.4 acres, Sunfish Park offers playgrounds, a multi-purpose court and lawn area.
Turnstone Park offers a 1.5 acres of playground equipment, a lawn area, and a basketball court. There's also a sand pit for the kids to play in.
Howes Play Lot is located near Union Avenue,  between Thomas and Howes Drives, off Anne Way. It is only accessible from Thomas Drive and Howes Drive.

The play lot is located on the corner of Oak Park Drive and Garden Lane, off of Los Gatos Boulevard.

A small neighborhood play lot with a playground and small lawn.

This is a bucket list playground for all older children. It is a wonderfully unique outdoor facility where staff encourage children to play and build creatively. Come climb on the many unusual kid designed and built forts, boats, and towers. Ride the zip line or hammer, saw, and paint. Adventure Playground is designed for children seven years old and older, however younger children are welcome as long as they are within arms reach of a participating adult. Everyone must wear sturdy shoes like tennis shoes and clothes that can get dirty! Entrance is free unless you want to use the drop in option, which is $10 per child over 7 years old for 3 hours. Open only on the weekend and weekdays during the summer.

Washington Park is the oldest park in Burlingame. The park is a year round center for community recreation. The Burlingame Recreation Division provides hundreds of classes and activities each year in the park and the Recreation Center. Tennis courts, a children’s playground, picnic areas, and baseball facilities are all in constant use.

The Olive Tot Lot is the smallest of all of the City's playgrounds, covering just a sliver of land in the shadow of Highway 101 off Olive Avenue. The site is packed with fun play equipment, including a "race track" and car wash for small trikes - perfect for younger children. There are two picnic tables and one barbecue grill under a wooden structure for shade. A four-seat permanent chess table is situated at the north end of the park, allowing play for older park-goers.

A historical site with large picnic areas (8 reservable sites) with BBQ's, open turf play areas, children's play equipment, a small lake and island with ducks and peacocks, off street parking and restrooms. A hiking trail provides access to the ridge of the Sulfur Springs Mountain for spectacular views of Vallejo and the Napa River.
This park at the center of town has a playground, gazebo and picnic tables. It can be reserved for private parties.

Roosevelt Park is located on Washington Street. The park has ample space and includes: a big kids play area, tots play area, an open field, skate park and community center. The big kids play area is located just off the major street and is partially fenced off from the street. There is a picnic area with a large BBQ pit, but this is located adjacent to the tot play area and skate park.

column3: La Herran Dr and Pruneridge Ave
column9: Westwood Oaks Park is a contains a small playground which is partially fenced in, completely on the street side. This park is dedicated for older kids, age 5-12, but also has little horses for tots to ride on. The park has a grass area for kids to run, and a path surrounding the park for riding your bike. The park also contains public bathrooms.

Live Oak Park is a small neighborhood park located next to Northside Branch Library. There are two play structures at the park, one for big kids and one for little kids. The paly area is made of sand with rubber making it handicap accessible. The park has 4 small picnic tables with individual BBQs that overlook the play structures. The restrooms are also located nearby so not a lot of traveling is required.

Willow Oaks Park, just off Willow street. The playground is enclused and there are two play strutures, good for older and younger kids. The material is made of mulch. 
The park also contains a baseball, soccer, 4 tennis courts and an enclosed dog park. The parking lot itself is very small sufficient for only 12 cars.

Encinal Park has a large grass field. On one side of the park there are two playground, one enclosed for tots, the other for big kids. The tot playground is fully enclosed. The park also has a tennis court, volley ball court and baseball diamond. Most of the picnic tables and BBQ pits are located near the tennis courts, which is far away from the playgrounds.

This small playground is action pack with three play structures. One for smaller kids age 2-5, with two slides and a sand pit. The other two play structures are for older kids, age 5-12 and are connected by monkey bars. Surfaces are primarily sand based with some rubber. The park is connected to two baseball fields and has a basketball court and tennis court attached.
Located off of Highway 24, Orinda's newest park has a tot lot, group picnic areas that can be reserved, two artificial turf fields for soccer, lacrosse, rugby and baseball.

Pine Grove is a designated multi-use, natural turf field with two ball diamonds, a soccer field in between, a tot lot, picnic areas adjacent to the ball fields, restrooms and storage. A walking trail was incorporated into the project to create a connection between the residential properties and the recreational facilities.

Kids love this ocean themed spray park. Summer hours are 12p-6p, 7 days/week, and May, Aug. and Sept. the water Feature will operate 3p-6p Mon-Fri and 12p-6p Weekends and the spray park is closed Oct - April. Call to confirm opening hours.

This 82-acre area is a popular place for family and group picnicking. It is known for its lush setting in a grove of fragrant second growth redwood trees off Skyline Boulevard in Oakland. The all accessible playground has an very large play structure with slides, ramps and climbing walls. The Roberts Pool complex features a 25 yard, heated outdoor swimming pool is located next to the playground.

Small fenced in neighborhood park providing only playground equipment for young children. Adult supervision is a necessity, given to proximity to the Rollins Road traffic. Right adjacent to highway 101 with the associated noise.
Small fenced playground with a small play structure and picnic area. Adult supervision is a necessity, given the proximity to the Carolan Avenue traffic.
Paloma Park is a small playground for young children. There is a single picnic table available.

Victoria Park is a small neighborhood park in the southeast section of Burlingame. The park has an upgraded playground, which is appropriate for young children. There is also a half court basketball court available for play. The park is notable for its grove of Coast Redwoods.

Ray Park is a neighborhood park that can accommodate a variety of activities simultaneously. There is a shaded playground, which is ideal for hot days. A two-acre turf area is home to the local Girls Softball Association. Tennis courts and a multi-use court round out the available facilities. Two picnic tables are available without reservations for small groups.

Village Park is a neighborhood park on the north end of town that bustles with activity.  On weekdays, between the hours of 10:00 am and 3:00 pm, groups of more than 15 people need written permission from the City's Parks & Recreation Director.
Local park with a modern play structure, swings and a climbing tower.
Small park with two court tennis courts and a children’s play area. There is a small sand box, one play structure and some swings.
Cute, little playground in downtown Burlingame, tucked away in the corner of a City parking lot.

Cuernavaca Park boasts a spectacular view of the Bay. It has radical elevation changes allowing the park to serve as a major green belt as well as a site for youth baseball and softball games. The children’s playground and basketball court are located at the highest elevation on the site. Park users often pause to view planes landing at the San Francisco airport.

Del Medio Park is a small park that has two play structures; one for big kids and one for little kids. There are two picnic tables overlooking the play area and park benches surrounding. The playground also has a sand pit, a grassy area for kids to run around and excercise equipment for adults to get a workout in.

This 20-acre park is known for the mosaic water-snake that winds down a hillside. The park has a children's play area, sand volleyball court, covered picnic area, lighted sports fields, and two tennis courts. The sports fields, tennis courts, picnic area, and a snack shack are available to rent 

Got a younger child who likes to explore? The playground located at Diablo Vista Park is ideal for kids 4 and under. Affectionately known as "Snake Park," this park's pint-sized climbing structures, bucket swings and large sandy area is perfect for toddlers. The park is divided into three play areas: one with small buildings, one with a climbing structure and slides, and one with swings.

The center point of the park is a large tile snake. The snake, topped with fountains and a cement pad, slithers down a hill, offering pint-sized climbers many different paths to explore. Kids who climb the snake will be treated to not only a bird's eye view of the park, but also a few fountains for water play.

Renovated and reopened in 2002, Douglass Playground has an excellent hillside location complete with trees and rock outcroppings on two levels. The lowest level includes a Clubhouse, children's play area, informal lawn areas and tennis courts. The upper level is heavily wooded and contains a baseball field. There are picnic tables, restrooms, and it is quite dog friendly!

Duboce Park features baby swings, play structures for kids and a sand play area. There is also a basketball court. The restrooms are located at the adjacent Harvey Milk Rec Center. The large grass field is a mecca for local dogs.

The park is located right next to the Harvey Milk Recreational Center, which offers a wealth of community programs which are free are very inexpensive.

Earl J. Carmichael Park is a large park that contains a baseball field, basketball court, and children's playground. The park itself has a dedicated parking lot. The play area is of older design, being made of wood for all ages and resides on sand. Surrounding the play area are benches for easy child supervision. The park contains picnic tables and BBQs pits. There is one large BBQ located next to the baseball field, but it probably requires reservations.

Alta Plaza Park features a playground and a large lawn area, two full tennis courts plus a multipurpose basketball/tennis court. There are plenty of paved walking trails, benches, and views of the City. There is a kids' lot that contains three different play structures, a sand lot, benches, slides and seven swings.

Everett Alvarez Jr. Park has two at structures, one for the 2-5 and one for the 5-12 age range. The play structures contain numerous slide and climbing structures. The play structures reside on sand and have rubber as well to be handicap accessible. There are numerous big kid and a few little kid swings. The picnic tables overlook the play area, and there is one shared BBQ. The play structure is fenced off from the street but is not fully enclosed. The park has public restrooms and the woman's restroom has a change table.
Glen Canyon Park has hiking trails to explore, plus a rec center with several facilities available to the public: two baseball fields, a tennis court, as well as George Christopher Playground.

Cataldi Park is just under 40 acres in size and has playgrounds for all age groups. The park has plenty of parking as well with four parking through out the park. 
The marjor play area is located just off Cataldi Dr & Morril Ave. The park also has 7 tennis courts, 1/2 basketball court & tons of grass area for kids to play.

Hap Magee Ranch Park (1025 La Gonda Way). Hap Magee has a storied past. A barn façade at the park entrance commemorates the park’s former life as a ranch for longhorn steer. Before the cattle called it home, the site was a summer camp for San Francisco orphans, known as Camp Swain. Look for a drinking fountain commemorating Camp Swain with a plaque and a brick rendering of children playing.

Hap Magee’s water feature is a combination of metal tubes that form a tunnel with water spraying inside as kids run through, and water spraying up from the ground. A motion sensor activates the feature on a random circuit. This 17-acre park also has walking trails, separate play areas for younger and older children, picnic areas, and a dog park.

column2: Gordon E. Oliver Eden Shores Park

column9: Cimarron Park has a large grass field and a playground dedicated for older kids. The park also contains a basketball court.

Henry Schmidt Park has a unique play area. The theme of the play area is the old west and is dedicated towards younger kids, aged 2-5, located on sand. Surrounding the play area are benches so kids can easily be supervised. There are picnic tables tables with individual BBQs throughout the park. The park also contains a tennis court and a baseball diamond.

Henry Seale Park contains play structures for both older and younger kids. The older kids play structure appears to be newer in construction. The playground also contains a sand pit, and a small club house for tots to play in. There are picnic benches overlooking the play area, but the picnic tables with BBQs are located further away. 
The park also has a walking trail and a large open grass field. It's used by both joggers and dog walkers alike.

Emma Prusch Farm Park has two major draws: a huge big kids play area and farm animals that can be fed. The park also contains a small kids area next to the big kids playground. The park has: chicken, goats, pigs, rabbits & cows. There are also a number of large reservable picnic areas.
